SATIRE VIII.

This is the account os a supper given by Nasidienus Rufus, a vain, rich gourmand. The nas-ration is in the mouth of the comio poet Fundanius, who was among the guenta. The entertainment appears to have been conspicuous for vulgar display; and the host’s affected, and perhaps blundering, gastro- nomy is ridiculed throughout. Much of the description may be compared with the rules of the Fourth Satire.
